@revshark Rev and I are fine. Thanks. I didnt jab at him we have differences of opinion that we have covered extensively and respectfully on @realmoney. This morning as I have had in past, I said both technical and fundamental analysis has lost SOME of its value over the

short term because of the dominance of products and strategies geared towards price momentum (e.g. quants, etfs). I really don't have time (I have two day jobs) to answer questions routinely on Twitter - and I am more off it than on it as a result. I don't hang out on Twitter.

dont have the time to take on challenges from all that disagree. If I responded to them all, I would be working thirty hours a day and not getting any work done. The fact is that I have been an advocate for you for years - that clearly was to no avail and came on deaf ears.

And, by the way, I see other influences (such as central bank liquidity, the popularity of ETFs and other factors) as making fundamental analysis less valuable in gauging stock prices over the short term, as well. @hmeisler @revshark

You are taking my comments that the dominance of passive strategies is making the charts and TA less useful and concluding, inaccurately, that I am saying TA is useless. Come on now, Rev - you know better than to write that, as I am not saying that at all.

You might think that these influences make it easier, Rev. But I think it makes it harder and, again, less predictable to rely on stock prices/charts because "price is not necessarily truth." Its artificial.

I have a different view, respectfully. And mine comes from my time frames. Charts ruined (and as a consequence TA loses SOME value) because of the dominance (75% of trading) of passive products/strategies that artificially influence the short term course of products.

Twitter is not the correct forum for this I have written thousands of world on @realmoney regarding the impact of passive products and strategies (etfs, risk parity etc) on trading and prices. The artificiality of these trend following products have made charts and TA less valued

@SullyCNBC Ask every bullish talking head to respond to this: Notwithstanding the strong and persistent price momentum I don't see the basis for further gains: * The Fed Is Pushing on A String: The Fed has now cut three times and there is no meaningful improvement in the domestic

economic data. Indeed, as mentioned in an earlier post, fourth-quarter Real GDP growth forecasts have moved to 1% or less from 3% in the first-quarter of 2019 and 1.9% in the third quarter. * Nor Are Some Stocks Higher From Easier Money: The Russell Index, supposed to be levered

to domestic growth, is only 1% higher since the first rate cut in July Meanwhile the CRB Index is down by over 3% and the 10-year TIPS breakeven is 20 basis points lower (to 1.55%) since that first cut in the federal funds rate. @SullyCNBC @fundstrat @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney
